                    <history>
                        <origin notBefore="1275" notAfter="1300" cert="high" evidence="conjecture">
                            <p>The fragment is written in <origPlace>Iceland</origPlace>. <name
                                    type="person" key="KriKaa001">Kristian Kålund</name> once dated
                                it <origDate>the fourteenth century</origDate> (<bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary-1" target="KKKat">KKKat</ref>
                                </bibl>). Later <name type="person" key="OscJoh001">Oscar Albert
                                    Johnsen</name> and <name type="person" key="JonHel003">Jón
                                    Helgason</name> dated it <origDate notBefore="1275"
                                    notAfter="1300" cert="high" evidence="conjecture">the last
                                    quarter of the thirteenth century</origDate> (<bibl>
                                    <ref type="secondary-1" target="OlHJH">Johnsen &amp; Jón
                                        Helgason 1941</ref>, p. 962</bibl>).</p>
                                 </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>A rather coarse seventeenth century hand has written on the old
                                writing verso: <q xml:lang="is">Steynun Olafs dotter  þessa Bok hia
                                        mi<expan>er</expan> Snæbirne Torffa syne An<expan>n</expan>o
                                    1643</q>. The man is probably the lawman <name type="person"
                                    key="SnaTor001">Snæbjörn Torfason</name> of <name type="place"
                                    >Kirjuból</name> in <name type="place">Langadal</name>, later of
                                    <name type="place">Bær</name> in <name type="place"
                                    >Króksfjörður</name> (d. 1666), Steinunn Ólafsdóttir cannot be
                                identified.</p>
                        </provenance>
